Part 1: Data

From the GSS codebook Appendix A, for the 1977+ surveys, the General Social Survey has been using a full probability sample. 1972 through 1974 surveys used a modified probability sample, which introduces the quota element at the block level. The 1975 and 1976 studies were conducted with a transitional sample design, viz., one-half full probability and one-half block quota. From the GSS codebook Appendix B, the data in this survey are collected through interviews, where interviewers answer questionnaires.

Since the data is collected through random sampling of the population instead of random assignment, the conclusions we draw from the sample is generalizable to the population, but we cannot conclude casual relations between the explanatory variable and response variable in our study.

Part 2: Research question

Research question 1: Public Opinion on Education Spending in the US In this question, I want to investigate the shift in public opinion on education spending in the US over time, more specifically, opinion on the amount of money spent on improving the nations education system. I want to answer the following three sub-questions:

1.1. What is the proportion of people in the US population who think theyre spending too little money on improving the nations education system in year 1972 - 2012, respectively?

1.2. Has the proportion of people who think theyre spending too little money on education increased from year 1972 to year 2012?

1.3. Is there a relationship between education level and the opinion on education spending in the U.S.?

Part 4: Inference

We will now study our first sub question by performing inference for a single proportion. Well work on the proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little on education in year 1973 in detail, then apply the same analysis for the other years.

Well compute the 95% confidence interval for the population proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little in year 1973 using the Central Limit Theorem. First, lets check the conditions for applying the CLT:

  1. Independence: as discussed in the Data section, the data is collected from random sampling. Sample size n = 1434, which is smaller than 10% of the US population in year 1973. Therefore, we can assume the samples are independent of each other.
educ %>%
  filter(year == 1973) %>%
  summarize(n())
##    n()
## 1 1434
  1. Sample size/skew: in the sample for year 1973, therere 734 success cases (Too Little) and 700 failures (other opinions), which satisfies the condition of 10 successes/failures.
educ %>%
  filter(year == 1973) %>%
  summarize(n_suc = sum(nateduc == "Too Little"), n_fail = n() - n_suc)
##   n_suc n_fail
## 1   734    700

The conditions are met. By CLT, the confidence interval for a population proportion is [ z^ ]

educ_1973 <- educ %>%
  filter(year == 1973) %>%
  mutate(opinion = ifelse(nateduc == "Too Little", "Too Little", "other"))

inference(y = opinion, data = educ_1973, statistic = "proportion", type = "ci", method = "theoretical", success = "Too Little")
## Single categorical variable, success: Too Little
## n = 1434, p-hat = 0.5119
## 95% CI: (0.486 , 0.5377)

We are 95% confident that the population proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little on education in the US in year 1973 is between 48.6% to 53.8%. That is to say, if we take the random sample of size n = 1434 repetitively and compute the confidence interval, 95% the times the CI would capture the true population proportion.

Lets use nest and inference to compute the 95% confidence interval for years 1973 - 2012.

# Make a new binary categorical variable "opinion"
educ <- educ %>%
  mutate(opinion = ifelse(nateduc == "Too Little", "Too Little", "other"))

# Group by year and nest the data
ci_prop_little <- educ %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  nest() %>%
  mutate(ci_data = map(data, ~ {
    suppressMessages(suppressWarnings({
      inf_output <- inference(y = opinion, data = ., statistic ="proportion", type = "ci", method = "theoretical", success = "Too Little", verbose = FALSE)
      c(lower = inf_output[[3]][1], upper = inf_output[[3]][2])
      })) 
    })) %>%
  unnest_wider(ci_data) %>%  # Expand `ci_data` into `lower` and `upper` columns
  mutate(p_hat = (lower + upper) / 2) %>%  # Calculate `p_hat`
  select(year, p_hat, lower, upper)

Lets plot the confidence interval of the population proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little on education in year 1973 - 2012:

ggplot(ci_prop_little, aes(x = year, y = p_hat)) + 
  geom_line(color = "deepskyblue", size = 1.2) +  # Thicker blue line for better visibility
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper), 
                  color = "darkblue", 
                  size = 1, 
                  shape = 21, 
                  fill = "white", # White fill for points
                  stroke = 1.5) +  # Thicker border around points
  labs(title = "Proportion of Opinion with Confidence Interval",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Proportion",
       caption = "Error bars represent 95% Confidence Intervals") + 
  theme_minimal() +  # Minimal theme for a clean look
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),  # Center title with larger font
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14),  # Larger x-axis title
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 14),  # Larger y-axis title
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),  # Larger axis text
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),  # Remove minor grid lines for a cleaner look
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "lightgrey")  # Light color for major grid lines
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

This plot shows the change in the proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little on education in the US population. Were 95% confident that the actual proportion falls within the confidence interval. This plot shows a clear upward trend in the proportion, taking the error in the estimation into consideration.

So far we have answered research question 1.1, lets work on question 1.2. From the plot above, we can see that the proportion of underfunded education has increased between year 1973 and 2012. To answer this question with more certainty, well perform a hypothesis test for comparing two independent proportions at 5% significance level.

The hypotheses

Let the population proportion of atheists in year 1973 be [p_1], and year 2012 be [p_2 ]. We want to test whether the population proportion has increased in year 2012 compared to year 1973. \[H_0: p_1 = p_2 \] \[H_A: p_2 > p_1 \]

Check conditions

(1) Independence Within groups: In year 1973 and 2012, both samples are obtained with random sampling from the population. In both years, the sample size is smaller than 10% of the US population of that year.

Between groups: The 1973 and 2012 sample are independence of each other.

educ %>%
  filter(year == 2012) %>%
  summarize(n())
##   n()
## 1 985

Therefore, we can assume the independence condition is met.

(2) Sample size/skew Previously we checked the success-failure condition for year 1973 is met. Lets check for year 2012 with the same method:

educ %>%
  filter(year == 2012) %>%
  summarize(n_suc = sum(nateduc == "Too Little"), n_fail = n() - n_suc)
##   n_suc n_fail
## 1   733    252

in the sample for year 2012, therere 733 success cases and 252 failures, which satisfies the condition of 10 successes/failures.

Lets perform the hypothesis test with inference:

ht_data <- educ %>%
  filter(year %in% c(1973, 2012))

inference(y = opinion, x = year, data = ht_data, statistic = "proportion", type = "ht", alternative = 'less', method = "theoretical", success = "Too Little")
## Warning: Explanatory variable was numerical, it has been converted
##               to categorical. In order to avoid this warning, first convert
##               your explanatory variable to a categorical variable using the
##               as.factor() function
## Warning: Missing null value, set to 0
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: Too Little)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_1973 = 1434, p_hat_1973 = 0.5119
## n_2012 = 985, p_hat_2012 = 0.7442
## H0: p_1973 =  p_2012
## HA: p_1973 < p_2012
## z = -11.4905
## p_value = < 0.0001

The result shows that the p-value is smaller than 0.0001, which is smaller than our significance level 0.05. Therefore we reject the null hypothesis. The data provide convincing evidence for the alternative hypothesis, aka, the proportion of people who think theyre spending Too Little on education in the US population has increased from year 1973 to year 2012.

To find out whether the education level, which is the respondents highest degree, is related to the respondents opinion on national spending on education, well perform a []-square independence test for these two categorical variables.

Lets first summarize our data into a two-way table:

# Create the two-way table with totals
two_way_table <- deg_educ %>%
  count(degree, nateduc) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = nateduc, values_from = n) %>%
  mutate(Total = `Too Little` + `Too Much` + `About Right`)  # Add row total for each degree

# Add column total for atheist and religious
two_way_table <- two_way_table %>%
  bind_rows(
    summarise(., degree = "Total", across(`Too Little`:Total, sum))
  )
# transpose the table
transposed_table <- two_way_table %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -degree, names_to = " ", values_to = "count") %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = degree, values_from = count)
# Display the table using `gt` for formatted output
transposed_table %>%
  gt() %>%
  tab_header(title = "Distribution of Opinion by Degree") %>%
  fmt_number(decimals = 0)
